properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls tonight through Wednesday night. Westerly winds over Lake Superior will lead to the development of snow squalls early this evening. Local snowfall accumulations of 15 to 25 cm will be possible under the most intense snow squalls tonight. Winds will shift to the northwest Wednesday morning pushing the snow squalls southward. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Extreme wind chills will again be possible over northern portions of the province overnight and Wednesday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Sant at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Long-lasting blizzard conditions with potentially damaging winds and persistent visibility near zero in blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong ridge of high pressure is in place over the Northwest Territories. With low pressure over Alaska, strong winds with blowing snow are expected for northern sections of the Dempster. Near the Richardson Mountains, winds will reach 90 km/h gusting to 120 at times resulting in blizzard conditions. Blizzard conditions are forecast to last through at least Wednesday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls continuing through Wednesday. Snow squalls will continue through the rest of the night and through Wednesday. Local snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are possible. These snow squalls are expected to shift later today or this evening. Some areas may receive higher snowfall amounts as a result. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A frontal system will continue to strengthen as it approaches the BC coast. Overnight, strong southeast winds will develop over Haida Gwaii. The southeast winds are expected to peak at 90 km/h gusting to 110 by later Wednesday morning. The frontal system will move rapidly to the east, and the strong winds are expected to ease early Wednesday evening. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm today through Wednesday afternoon. Maximum wind gusts: 80 to 110 km/h. Locations: Nain to Makkovik Time span: Wednesday morning until Wednesday evening. Remarks: Fresh snowfall will combine with strengthening westerly winds Wednesday morning to produce poor visibility in blowing snow. Conditions should improve Wednesday evening. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
